Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{2}":[261,261],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{3}":[262,262],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{4}":[263,263],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{5}":[264,264],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{6}":[265,265],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{7}":[266,266],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{8}":[267,267],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{9}":[268,268],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation#{10}":[269,270],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 2: Find the Equation":[271,280],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 2: Find the Equation#{1}":[273,274],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 2: Find the Equation#{2}":[275,275],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 2: Find the Equation#{3}":[276,276],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 2: Find the Equation#{4}":[277,278],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 2: Find the Equation#{5}":[279,280],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 3: Shifted Ellipse":[281,298],"##10. Worked Examples#Example 3: Shifted Ellipse#{1}":[283,298],"##11. Visualization":[299,346],"##11. Visualization#Shape vs Eccentricity":[301,313],"##11. Visualization#Shape vs Eccentricity#{1}":[303,313],"##11. Visualization#The Defining Sum Property":[314,327],"##11. Visualization#The Defining Sum Property#{1}":[316,327],"##11. Visualization#Foci, Vertices, Latus Rectum":[328,346],"##11. Visualization#Foci, Vertices, Latus Rectum#{1}":[330,346],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning":[347,404],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.1 Ellipsoidal Level Sets of the Gaussian Distribution":[349,358],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.1 Ellipsoidal Level Sets of the Gaussian Distribution#{1}":[351,358],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.2 Covariance Ellipse and Principal Component Analysis (PCA)":[359,368],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.2 Covariance Ellipse and Principal Component Analysis (PCA)#{1}":[361,368],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.3 Trust Region Methods in Optimization":[369,378],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.3 Trust Region Methods in Optimization#{1}":[371,378],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.4 The Fisher Information Ellipse and Natural Gradient":[379,386],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.4 The Fisher Information Ellipse and Natural Gradient#{1}":[381,386],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.5 Elliptic Embeddings and Knowledge Graphs":[387,394],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.5 Elliptic Embeddings and Knowledge Graphs#{1}":[389,394],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.6 Elliptical Attention and Anisotropic Kernels":[395,404],"##12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning#12.6 Elliptical Attention and Anisotropic Kernels#{1}":[397,404],"##13. Ellipse vs Other Conics — At a Glance":[405,417],"##13. Ellipse vs Other Conics — At a Glance#{1}":[407,417],"##References":[418,427],"##References#{1}":[420,420],"##References#{2}":[421,421],"##References#{3}":[422,422],"##References#{4}":[423,424],"##References#{5}":[425,427]},"outlinks":[{"title":"0, 2\\pi)$$\n\nVerify: $\\frac{a^2\\cos^2 t}{a^2} + \\frac{b^2\\sin^2 t}{b^2} = \\cos^2 t + \\sin^2 t = 1$. ✓\n\n- $t = 0$: right vertex $(a, 0)$\n- $t = \\pi/2$: top co-vertex $(0, b)$\n- $t = \\pi$: left vertex $(-a, 0)$\n\n**Velocity:** $\\dot{\\mathbf{r}} = (-a\\sin t,, b\\cos t)$\n\n**Speed:** $|\\dot{\\mathbf{r}}| = \\sqrt{a^2\\sin^2 t + b^2\\cos^2 t}$\n\nThe arc length integral $\\int_0^{2\\pi}|\\dot{\\mathbf{r}}|,dt$ is exactly the elliptic integral $4aE(e)$ above.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Polar Form (Focus at Pole)\n\nWith one focus at the origin:\n\n$$r = \\frac{a(1-e^2)}{1 - e\\cos\\theta} = \\frac{b^2/a}{1 - e\\cos\\theta} = \\frac{\\ell}{1 - e\\cos\\theta}$$\n\nwhere $\\ell = \\frac{b^2}{a}$ is the **semi-latus rectum**.\n\n|$\\theta$|$r$|\n|---|---|\n|$0$ (periapsis)|$r_{\\min} = a(1-e) = a - c$|\n|$\\pi$ (apoapsis)|$r_{\\max} = a(1+e) = a + c$|\n|$\\pi/2$|$r = \\ell = b^2/a$|\n\nNote: $r_{\\min} + r_{\\max} = 2a$, consistent with $|PF_1| + |PF_2| = 2a$ at the vertices.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Conjugate Diameters and the General Equation\n\n### General Second-Degree Form\n\n$$Ax^2 + Bxy + Cy^2 + Dx + Ey + F = 0$$\n\nis an ellipse when $B^2 - 4AC < 0$ (and the conic is non-degenerate).\n\nReduce by completing the square → shifted standard form.\n\n### Matrix Form\n\n$$\\mathbf{x}^\\top M \\mathbf{x} = 1, \\quad M = \\begin{pmatrix} 1/a^2 & 0 \\ 0 & 1/b^2 \\end{pmatrix}$$\n\nFor a rotated ellipse: $M$ is a positive definite symmetric matrix. Its eigenvalues are $1/a^2$ and $1/b^2$; its eigenvectors are the axes of the ellipse.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Worked Examples\n\n### Example 1: Find Everything from the Equation\n\nGiven $\\dfrac{x^2}{25} + \\dfrac{y^2}{9} = 1$.\n\n- $a^2 = 25 \\Rightarrow a = 5$ (major axis horizontal, larger denominator)\n- $b^2 = 9 \\Rightarrow b = 3$\n- $c = \\sqrt{25 - 9} = \\sqrt{16} = 4$\n- $e = c/a = 4/5 = 0.8$\n- Foci: $(\\pm 4, 0)$\n- Vertices: $(\\pm 5, 0)$\n- Co-vertices: $(0, \\pm 3)$\n- Latus rectum: $2b^2/a = 18/5 = 3.6$\n- Area: $\\pi \\cdot 5 \\cdot 3 = 15\\pi$\n\n### Example 2: Find the Equation\n\nFoci at $(0, \\pm 3)$, sum of distances $= 10$.\n\n- Foci on $y$-axis → vertical major axis\n- $2a = 10 \\Rightarrow a = 5$, so $a^2 = 25$\n- $c = 3$, so $b^2 = a^2 - c^2 = 25 - 9 = 16$\n\n$$\\frac{x^2}{16} + \\frac{y^2}{25} = 1$$\n\n### Example 3: Shifted Ellipse\n\n$4x^2 + 9y^2 - 16x + 18y - 11 = 0$\n\nComplete the square:\n\n$4(x^2 - 4x) + 9(y^2 + 2y) = 11$\n\n$4(x-2)^2 - 16 + 9(y+1)^2 - 9 = 11$\n\n$4(x-2)^2 + 9(y+1)^2 = 36$\n\n$$\\frac{(x-2)^2}{9} + \\frac{(y+1)^2}{4} = 1$$\n\nCenter $(2, -1)$, $a = 3$, $b = 2$, $c = \\sqrt{5}$, horizontal major axis.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Visualization\n\n### Shape vs Eccentricity\n\n```\n  e = 0 (circle)        e = 0.6               e = 0.95\n       ___                _______            _______________\n      /   \\              /       \\          /               \\\n     |  ·  |            | ·   ·  |        | ·             · |\n      \\___/              \\_______/          \\_______________/\n\n  a = b               a > b               a >> b\n  c = 0               c = 0.6a            c = 0.95a\n```\n\n### The Defining Sum Property\n\n```\n            P\n           /|\\\n     r₁  /  |  \\ r₂\n         /   |   \\\n        /    |    \\\n       F₁    |    F₂\n   (-c, 0)   |   (c, 0)\n\n   r₁ + r₂ = 2a   (no matter where P is on the ellipse)\n```\n\n### Foci, Vertices, Latus Rectum\n\n```\n              (0, b)\n                *\n                |\n                | ← b\n                |\n(-a,0)*---F₁*---+---*F₂---*(a,0)\n        (-c,0)  |  (c,0)\n                |\n                * (0,-b)\n\n  Latus rectum (through F₂, ⊥ to major axis):\n  length = 2b²/a\n```\n\n---\n\n## 12. Connection to AI, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning\n\n### 12.1 Ellipsoidal Level Sets of the Gaussian Distribution\n\nThe multivariate Gaussian:\n\n$$p(\\mathbf{x}) = \\frac{1}{(2\\pi)^{d/2}|\\Sigma|^{1/2}}\\exp!\\left(-\\frac{1}{2}(\\mathbf{x}-\\boldsymbol{\\mu})^\\top\\Sigma^{-1}(\\mathbf{x}-\\boldsymbol{\\mu})\\right)$$\n\nhas **ellipsoidal level sets**. The equation $(\\mathbf{x}-\\boldsymbol{\\mu})^\\top\\Sigma^{-1}(\\mathbf{x}-\\boldsymbol{\\mu}) = k^2$ is the $d$-dimensional ellipsoid (ellipse in 2D) with axes aligned to the eigenvectors of $\\Sigma$, with semi-axis lengths $k\\sqrt{\\lambda_i}$ where $\\lambda_i$ are eigenvalues of $\\Sigma$.\n\nEvery time you compute a Gaussian distribution — in a VAE, a Kalman filter, a Gaussian process, naive Bayes — you are computing with ellipses.\n\n### 12.2 Covariance Ellipse and Principal Component Analysis (PCA)\n\nPCA finds the axes of the **covariance ellipse** of the data:\n\n$$\\hat{\\Sigma} = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{i=1}^n (\\mathbf{x}_i - \\bar{\\mathbf{x}})(\\mathbf{x}_i - \\bar{\\mathbf{x}})^\\top$$\n\nThe principal components are the eigenvectors of $\\hat{\\Sigma}$, and the eigenvalues $\\lambda_1 \\geq \\lambda_2 \\geq \\cdots$ are the **squared semi-axes** of the data's covariance ellipse. The eccentricity of this ellipse measures how much the data varies in one direction vs another — a nearly circular covariance ellipse means all directions are equally informative; a thin, elongated ellipse means the data lies nearly on a line.\n\nDimensionality reduction = projecting onto the longest axes of the ellipse.\n\n### 12.3 Trust Region Methods in Optimization\n\n**Trust region** optimization (used in second-order methods like TRPO in reinforcement learning) constrains the update step $\\Delta\\mathbf{w}$ to lie inside an ellipsoidal region:\n\n$$\\Delta\\mathbf{w}^\\top H,\\Delta\\mathbf{w} \\leq \\delta$$\n\nwhere $H$ is the Hessian (or Fisher information matrix). This is an ellipsoid in parameter space — its shape is determined by the local curvature of the loss. Directions of high curvature get short semi-axes (small allowed steps); directions of low curvature get long semi-axes. The optimal step is the eigenvector of $H$ corresponding to the steepest descent direction, constrained to this ellipsoid.\n\n**TRPO** (Trust Region Policy Optimization) uses a KL-divergence ellipsoid to constrain policy updates — the geometry is fundamentally ellipsoidal.\n\n### 12.4 The Fisher Information Ellipse and Natural Gradient\n\nThe **Fisher information matrix** $\\mathcal{F}$ defines a Riemannian metric on the parameter space of a statistical model. Its level sets are ellipses. The **natural gradient**:\n\n$$\\tilde{\\nabla}\\mathcal{L} = \\mathcal{F}^{-1}\\nabla\\mathcal{L}$$\n\nrescales the gradient to account for the ellipsoidal geometry of the parameter space. Standard gradient descent treats parameter space as isotropic (circular level sets); natural gradient descent uses the true ellipsoidal geometry. This is why natural gradient / K-FAC methods converge faster — they respect the intrinsic ellipsoidal structure.\n\n### 12.5 Elliptic Embeddings and Knowledge Graphs\n\nRecent work (Vilnis et al., Box Embeddings; Peng et al., Hyperbolic Embeddings) embeds entities in ellipsoidal regions rather than points. An entity is represented as a Gaussian (equivalently, an ellipse in 2D), and entailment/subsumption is modeled as **containment of ellipses**:\n\n$$\\text{\"A is-a B\"} \\iff \\text{ellipse}_A \\subset \\text{ellipse}_B$$\n\nThe volume of the ellipse ($\\pi ab$) encodes the generality of the concept: large ellipses = general concepts, small ellipses = specific ones.\n\n### 12.6 Elliptical Attention and Anisotropic Kernels\n\nStandard dot-product attention computes $\\text{softmax}(\\mathbf{q}^\\top\\mathbf{k}/\\sqrt{d})$ — a spherical similarity. **Elliptical attention** generalizes this to:\n\n$$\\text{score}(\\mathbf{q}, \\mathbf{k}) = \\exp!\\left(-(\\mathbf{q}-\\mathbf{k})^\\top M (\\mathbf{q}-\\mathbf{k})\\right)$$\n\nwhere $M$ is a learned positive definite matrix. The similarity decays along ellipsoidal contours, allowing the model to learn anisotropic feature relevance — some feature dimensions matter more than others for a given query.\n\n---\n\n## 13. Ellipse vs Other Conics — At a Glance\n\n|Property|Circle|Ellipse|Parabola|Hyperbola|\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n|Equation|$x^2+y^2=r^2$|$\\frac{x^2}{a^2}+\\frac{y^2}{b^2}=1$|$x^2=4py$|$\\frac{x^2}{a^2}-\\frac{y^2}{b^2}=1$|\n|Discriminant $B^2-4AC$|$<0$|$<0$|$=0$|$>0$|\n|Eccentricity $e$|$0$|$0 < e < 1$|$1$|$e > 1$|\n|Foci|1 (center)|2|1|2|\n|Sum/diff of distances|$-$|$|PF_1|+|\n|Closed curve?|Yes|Yes|No|No|\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n1. **Stewart, James.** _Calculus: Early Transcendentals_, 8th ed. Appendix C — Conic Sections; §10.6 — Conic Sections in Polar Coordinates.\n2. **MIT 18.02 Multivariable Calculus** — Quadratic forms, ellipsoids, covariance geometry. [ocw.mit.edu","target":"https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/18-02sc-multivariable-calculus-fall-2010/","line":203}],"metadata":{"tags":["#ellipse","#conic-sections","#calculus","#geometry","#ML-connections","#covariance","#optimization"]},"task_lines":[],"tasks":{},"codeblock_ranges":[[17,30],[144,153],[303,312],[316,326],[330,343]]},"smart_blocks:01.Maths/Calculus/10.Parametric Equations and Polar Coordinates/18.Ellipse.md#": {"path":null,"last_embed":{"hash":null},"embeddings":{},"text":null,"length":0,"last_read":{"hash":"1covs37","at":1776558783718},"key":"01.Maths/Calculus/10.Parametric Equations and Polar Coordinates/18.Ellipse.md#","lines":[3,6],"size":190,"outlinks":[],"class_name":"SmartBlock"},
